# PART B: Rate Limiting (Phase 5)

## Why Rate Limiting?

Without rate limiting, anyone can:
- Spam your `/api/shorten` endpoint → create millions of fake URLs
- Overload your server with requests → crash it (DoS attack)

Rate limiting says: **"You get X requests per Y minutes. That's it."**

---

## Step 1: Create Rate Limiter Middleware

Create `server/middleware/rateLimiter.js`:

```javascript
// server/middleware/rateLimiter.js

const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// General API rate limiter
// Applied to all /api/* routes
// Limit: 100 requests per 15 minutes per IP
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const apiLimiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,   // 15 minutes in milliseconds
  max: 100,                    // max 100 requests per windowMs per IP
  
  // Custom error message when limit exceeded
  message: {
    error: 'Too many requests from this IP. Please try again after 15 minutes.',
    retryAfter: '15 minutes',
  },
  
  // standardHeaders: true adds RateLimit-* headers to responses
  // So the client knows how many requests they have left
  standardHeaders: true,
  
  // legacyHeaders: false disables the old X-RateLimit-* headers
  legacyHeaders: false,
});

// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Strict limiter for shorten endpoint
// This endpoint is expensive (DB write) — be more strict
// Limit: 10 requests per minute per IP
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const shortenLimiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 60 * 1000,   // 1 minute
  max: 10,               // max 10 shortening requests per minute
  
  message: {
    error: 'You are creating URLs too fast. Max 10 per minute.',
    tip: 'Slow down! This limit exists to prevent spam.',
  },
  
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
});

module.exports = { apiLimiter, shortenLimiter };
```

---

## Step 2: Apply Rate Limiters

Update `server/index.js`:

```javascript
const { apiLimiter } = require('./middleware/rateLimiter');

// Apply general rate limiter to ALL /api routes
app.use('/api', apiLimiter);

// Apply to routes
app.use('/api', urlRoutes);
app.use('/api/analytics', analyticsRoutes);
```

Update `server/routes/url.routes.js` for the strict shorten limiter:

```javascript
const { shortenLimiter } = require('../middleware/rateLimiter');

// Apply strict limiter ONLY to the shorten endpoint
router.post('/shorten', shortenLimiter, shortenUrl);
```

---

## Test Rate Limiting

Using Thunder Client, send 11 POST requests to `/api/shorten` quickly.

The 11th request should return:
```json
{
  "error": "You are creating URLs too fast. Max 10 per minute.",
  "tip": "Slow down! This limit exists to prevent spam."
}
```

Check the response headers — you'll see:
```
RateLimit-Limit: 10
RateLimit-Remaining: 0
RateLimit-Reset: 1234567890
```

---

## ✅ Phase 4 & 5 Checklist

- [ ] Analytics controller created with 5 endpoints
- [ ] Analytics routes created
- [ ] Analytics routes wired in `index.js`
- [ ] Test all analytics endpoints in Thunder Client
- [ ] `rateLimiter.js` middleware created
- [ ] `apiLimiter` applied to all `/api` routes
- [ ] `shortenLimiter` applied to POST `/shorten`
- [ ] Test: 11th request is blocked

---

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **MongoDB Aggregation Pipeline** is one of the most important skills for backend interviews.
> The `$match → $group → $sort → $project` pattern is used everywhere.
> Practice explaining each stage out loud!

> [!NOTE]
> **Interview Q:** "How would you prevent API abuse?"
> **Answer:** Rate limiting by IP using sliding window or token bucket algorithm. Express-rate-limit implements a fixed window approach. For production, Redis-backed rate limiting is more accurate across multiple server instances.

